'''Moss Airport, Rygge''' {{Airport codes|RYG|ENRY}} ({{lang-no|Moss lufthavn, Rygge}}) is an [[international airport]] serving [[Oslo]] and [[Eastern Norway]], located in [[Rygge]]. It is both a [[regional airport]] for [[<U+00D8>stfold]] as well as an airport for [[low-cost airline]]s. The airport is located {{convert|10|km}} outside [[Moss, Norway|Moss]] and {{convert|60|km}} outside Oslo and is owned and operated by the private company Rygge Sivile Lufthavn AS. It is co-located with [[Rygge Air Station]], operated by the [[Royal Norwegian Air Force]], who also own the land and runway and operate the [[air traffic control]]. In addition to charter flights, the airport is a base for [[Ryanair]] and [[Norwegian Air Shuttle]].

The airport opened on 8 October 2007, but did not officially opened until 14 February 2008, when regular scheduled services started. In March 2010, Ryanair established a base at the airport, and has moved most of its Oslo-bound flights from [[Sandefjord Airport, Torp]]. The airport has a capacity for 2 million passengers per year, but cannot reach this because of [[concession (contract)|concession]] limit of 21,000 annual air movements. The airport had 619,000 passengers in 2009. Moss Airport, Rygge has an [[airport rail link]], via a shuttle bus, at [[Rygge Station]].

==Facilities==
The airport is a joint military and civilian airport located in the municipality of Rygge, west of the lake [[Vansj<U+00F8>]].<ref name=vansjo /> The airport is primarily an international, low-cost airport, but also serves as a domestic regional airport for <U+00D8>stfold and Follo. The airport is owned by the [[Norwegian Defence Estates Agency]], while the civilian terminal is owned by Rygge Sivile Lufthavn AS ("Rygge Civilian Airport"), a private company owned by the [[Thon Group]] (40%), the [[Orkla Group]] (40%), [[<U+00D8>stfold Energi]] (15%) and [[<U+00D8>stfold County Municipality]] (5%).<ref name=facts>{{cite web |url=http://www.en.ryg.no/kat/000005.asp |title=Information about Moss Airport Rygge |publisher=Rygge Sivile Lufthavn |accessdate=25 November 2010}}</ref>

[[File:Moss Airport, Rygge.JPG|thumb|left|Arrival hall]]
The terminal building is {{convert|16000|m2|sp=us}}, and is dimensioned for 2 million passengers annually.<ref name=facts>{{cite web |url=http://www.en.ryg.no/kat/000049.asp |title=Technical facts |publisher=Rygge Sivile Lufthavn |accessdate=25 November 2010}}</ref> The airport has kiosks,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.en.ryg.no/kat/000012.asp |title=Point kiosks |publisher=Rygge Sivile Lufthavn |accessdate=25 November 2010}}</ref>[[automatic teller machine]]s <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.en.ryg.no/kat/000018.asp |title=Currency exchange |publisher=Rygge Sivile Lufthavn |accessdate=25 November 2010}}</ref> and two [[duty free]] stores, one for departure and one for arrival.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.en.ryg.no/kat/000013.asp |title=Duty-free |publisher=Rygge Sivile Lufthavn |accessdate=25 November 2010}}</ref> There are also restaurants, caf<U+00E9>s and car rentals. The terminal has opening hours from 06:30 to 23:30.<ref name=facts /> There are seven gates and aircraft stands, of which two can switch between domestic and international departures.<ref name=gates>{{cite news |title=F<U+00F8>rste fly letter fra Rygge i oktober  |work=[[Aftenposten]] |last=Engstr<U+00F6>m |first=Josefin |date=31 January 2007 |page=4 |language=Norwegian}}</ref>

The runway is {{convert|2442|m|sp=us}} long and {{convert|45|m|sp=us}} wide.<ref name=facts /> It is equipped with [[instrument landing system]] Category II using solely [[light emitting diode]]s (LED) as lights. This allows landing with {{convert|300|m|sp=us}} visibility.<ref name=led>{{cite news |url=http://www.tu.no/motor/article268343.ece |title=LEDer flyene ned |work=[[Teknisk Ukeblad]] |last=Dall<U+00F8>kken |first=Per Erlien |date=22 November 2010 |accessdate=23 November 2010 |archivedate=23 November 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5uSWsE1cF |language=Norwegian}}</ref> The airport has a [[taxiway]] and an [[de-icing]] platform.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ippc.no/norway_aip/current/AIP/AD/ENRY/EN_AD_2_ENRY_en.pdf |title=ENRY <U+2013> Moss/Rygge |publisher=[[Avinor]] |accessdate=25 November 2010}}</ref>

===Military===
{{main|Rygge Air Station}}

Rygge Air Station is home to the [[No. 720 Sqadron NoRAF|720 Squadron]] of the Royal Norwegian Air Force (NoRAF), which operates [[Bell 412]] helicopters, the [[No. 717 Sqadron NoRAF|717 Squadron]] which operates [[Dassault Falcon 20]] jets, and a detachment of the [[No. 330 Sqadron NoRAF|330 Squadron]] which operates [[Westland Sea King]] [[search and rescue]] helicopters. The air station also hosts several support functions, including education, logistics of the air force, and branch of the [[Norwegian Home Guard]]. The military run all common functions of the airport, such as the runway, fire and rescue service, and the air traffic control.<ref name=mil>{{cite web |url=http://www.mil.no/luft/start/omlf/stasjoner/rygge/ |title=Rygge |publisher=[[Royal Norwegian Air Force]] |accessdate=24 November 2010 |archivedate=24 November 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5uTsyOEUM |language=Norwegian}}</ref>

==Airlines and destinations==
[[File:RYG destinations.svg|thumb|International destinations from Rygge]]

Rygge is a hub for both Norwegian Air Shuttle and Ryanair.<ref name=norwegianhub /><ref name=ryanairhub /> In addition, there are charter services to the Mediterranean.<ref name=gates /> The airport had 619,000 passengers in 2009. Estimates indicate that the airport will have about 1.5 million passengers in 2010.<ref name=led>{{cite news |url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/distrikt/ostfold/1.6938837 |title=Passasjerantallet p<U+00E5> Rygge <U+00F8>kte |work=[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation]] |last=Pedersen |first=Lars H<U+00E5>kon |date=9 January 2010 |accessdate=25 November 2010 |archivedate=25 November 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5uVSgRBSX |language=Norwegian}}</ref>

