==Ground transport==
[[File:Rygge stasjon with 72b.jpg|thumb|[[Rygge Station]] with a [[NSB Class 73|Class 73B]] [[electric multiple unit]] of the [[Norwegian State Railways]]]]

The airport is located {{convert|4|km|sp=us}} from [[Rygge Station]] on the [[<U+00D8>stfold Line]].<ref name=dbfaktaboks /> The station is {{convert|69.28|km|sp=us}} from [[Oslo Central Station]] (Oslo&nbsp;S) and is served by the[[Norwegian State Railways]], who operate an hourly regional train service between Oslo and Halden using [[NSB Class 73]] [[electric multiple unit]]s, with an extra departure in the rush hour. Five of the daily services continue onwards south to [[Gothenburg]], Sweden. Travel time to Oslo&nbsp;S is 50 minutes, to Halden is 55 minutes, and to Gothenburg&nbsp;C is 3 hours and 3 minutes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nsb.no/getfile.php/www.nsb.no/nsb.no/Bilder/Rutetabeller/PDF-01-Oslo-Halden-2010-2%281%29.pdf |title=Oslo S <U+2013> Halden <U+2013> G<U+00F6>teborg |publisher=[[Norwegian State Railways]] |accessdate=6 November 2010}}</ref> NSB operates a free shuttle bus to Moss Airport, Rygge, which takes 8 minutes.<ref name=nsb>{{cite web |url=http://www.nsb.no/stations_or/rygge-station-article26531-2771.html |title=Rygge |publisher=[[Norwegian State Railways]] |accessdate=6 November 2010}}</ref> There is a waiting room in the station building<ref name=reopen>{{cite web |title=Gjen<U+00E5>pner stasjonsbygget p<U+00E5> Rygge |url=http://www.moss-avis.no/nyheter/gjenapner-stasjonsbygget-pa-rygge-1.5806128 |last=Foss |first=Ole Christian |work=[[Moss Avis]] |date=15 November 2010 |accessdate=16 November 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5uHkscS7j |archivedate=16 November 2010}}</ref> and [[ticket machine]]s.<ref name=nsb />

Moss Airport, Rygge is located {{convert|67|km|sp=us}} from Oslo; this compares to {{convert|49|km|sp=us}} for Gardermoen and {{convert|120|km|sp=us}} for Torp.<ref name=nasdist /> The terminal building is located next to [[European route E6|European Route E6]]. The airport is located 45 minutes from Oslo, {{convert|13|km|sp=us}} and 12 minutes from Moss, {{convert|27|km|sp=us}} and 25 minutes from [[Fredrikstad]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.en.ryg.no/kat/000057.asp |title=Private car |publisher=Rygge Sivile Lufthavn |accessdate=25 November 2010}}</ref> Access to Buskerud runs via the [[Oslofjord Tunnel]], while [[Vestfold]] is available via the [[Moss<U+2013>Horten Ferry]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.en.ryg.no/kat/000009.asp |title=How to arrive at Rygge |publisher=Rygge Sivile Lufthavn |accessdate=25 November 2010}}</ref> There is parking for 2,500 cars at the airport.<ref name=facts />

[[UniBuss]] operates Rygge-Ekspressen from Oslo with a travel time of 60 minutes. The service runs in correspondence with all of Norwegian's and Ryanair's flights, leaving 2 hours and 40 minutes before departure.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ryggeekspressen.no/EnglishInformation/tabid/121/language/nb-NO/Default.aspx |title=Rygge-Ekspressen |publisher=[[UniBuss]] |accessdate=25 November 2010}}</ref> [[Norway Bussekspress]] operates the service Flybussekspressen, which runs from Fredrikstad via Moss Airport, Rygge, Moss and Follo to Oslo Airport, Gardermoen. Travel time to Fredrikstad is 30 minutes, and travel time to Gardermoen is 1 hour and 40 minutes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bestilling.nor-way.no/nbeiis/statictable/statictable.aspx?Language=e&Route=F11&Direction=T&Product=P4 |title=Flybussekspressen |publisher=[[Norway Bussekspress]] |accessdate=25 November 2010}}</ref>

==History==
The first aerodrome at Rygge was built in 1942 and 1943, but was located about {{convert|2|km|sp=us}} west from the current runway. The aerodrome was closed in 1945, but reopened in 1949 as a military aviation school, although the school only remained for two years. In 1952 it was decided that Rygge was to become a military air station which met [[NATO]] specifications. This included the [[expropriation]] of {{convert|600|ha}} of land, costing NOK 12 million. The new Rygge Main Air Station was established on 15 September 1954, after investments of NOK 127 million. The old airport was closed and remained a camp until it was closed in 2003. Rygge Main Air Station hosted the [[No. 332 Squadron RNoAF|332 Squadron]], and later the [[No. 336 Squadron RNoAF|336 Squadron]] and the [[No. 330 Squadron RNoAF|330 Squadron]]. From 2003, the figher jets were moved from Rygge to [[Bod<U+00F8> Main Air Station]].<ref name=mil />

[[File:Rygge Air Station control tower.jpg|thumb|left|upright|The [[control towner]] at Rygge in 1983]]
On 8 October 1998, the main airport serving Oslo and Eastern Norway was moved from [[Oslo Airport, Fornebu]] to [[Oslo Airport, Gardermoen]].{{cn}} Several other locations, including [[Hurum]], [[Hob<U+00F8>l]] and [[<U+00C5>s]], had been considered, all which were located closer to Oslo and the [[Oslofjord]] area. The choice of location was controversial, in part because Gardermoen would be located further than Fornebu from among other things <U+00D8>stfold and Follo.<ref>{{cite book |title=Oslo lufthavn Gardermoen: Porten til Norge |last=Bredal |first=Dag |year=1998 |publisher=Schibsted |language=Norwegian |isbn=82-516-1719-7 |page=15}}</ref> In 1998, a report was made by SCC Trafikon which concluded that by building a civilian section at Rygge Air Station, it would be possible to generate 130,000 passengers per year, of which 40,000 would be charter travels. This was a higher passenger potential than Torp.  Several regional airlines, such as [[Teddy Air]], [[Air Stord]] and [[Coast Air]], all stated that they could be interested in routes from Rygge, while [[Scandinavian Airlines]], [[Braathens]] and [[Wider<U+00F8>e]] stated that they were not interested in flying from the airport. The idea was initially supported by local parliamentarians, <U+00D8>stfold County Council and the [[Confederation of Norwegian Enterprise]]. The latter stated that the most important air routes were those to Gardermoen and Torp, while the Trafikon report recommended routes to Bergen, Stavanger, Trondheim and Copenhagen.<ref>{{cite news |title=Flyselskapene i k<U+00F8> for Rygge |work=[[Aftenposten]] |last=Enghaug |first=P<U+00E5>l |date=24 August 1998 |language=Norwegian}}</ref>

In February 1999, [[Minister of Transport and Communications (Norway)|Minister of Transport and Communications]] [[Dag Jostein Fj<U+00E6>rvoll]] stated that he supported the opening of civilian traffic from Rygge.<ref>{{cite news |title=Liten interesse hos flyselskaper for Rygge |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=18 February 1999 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> Estimates from then were for an investment of 80 million [[Norwegian krone]] for a capacity of 150,000 annual passengers.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sivil flyplass p<U+00E5> Rygge vil koste 60-80 millioner  |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=19 February 1999 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> However, the plans allowed for further expansion to 500,000 annual passengers.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rygge <U+00E5>pner for 500 000 passasjerer |work=[[Aftenposten]] |last=Enghaug |first=P<U+00E5>l |date=19 February 1999 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> In July, the operating company Rygge Sivile Lufthavn was established. Owners were [[Borregaard]] (46.7%), <U+00D8>stfold County Municipality (20%), [[M. Peterson & S<U+00F8>n]] (16.6%) and [[Capricorn Invest]] (16.6%). The share capital was initially NOK 3 million. Egil Ulleb<U+00F8> was appointed the company's chair. According to the plans, the company would need NOK 50 million in share capital, and the [[Norwegian Civil Airport Administration]] was intended to own 34% of the airport.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rygge klar for takeoff |work=[[Dagens N<U+00E6>ringsliv]] |last=Larsen |first=Trygve |date=3 July 1999 |page=9 |language=Norwegian}}</ref>

On 12 January 2000, [[K<U+00F8>benhavns Lufthavne]], which operates among other things [[Copenhagen Airport]], bought 33.3% of the shares in Rygge Sivile Lufthavn. The company stated that they had invited the Norwegian Civil Airport Administration to purchase part of the company, but that no decision had been made by the government agency. The company stated that they were therefore forced to invite a foreign airport operate to purchase part of the company to have sufficient competence in airport operations.<ref>{{cite news |title=Vil konkurrere med Gardermoen: Kastrup kj<U+00F8>per seg inn i Rygge |work=[[Aftenposten]] |last=Kluge |first=Lars |date=13 January 2000 |page=2 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> In December, the Norwegian Civil Airport Administration stated that they were negative to the plans for civilian traffic at Rygge. The administration operates with the model that the large airports, in particular Gardermoen, make a profit, which is used to finance the deficits at smaller airports. The administration stated that establishing a civilian airport at Rygge would undermine the financial structure of Norwegian airports and would breach the political presumptions for constructing Gardermoen. If the administration was to be able to complete on price with Rygge, the state would have to give the necessary grants to cover the deficits at other airports. At the same time, Torp was required to pay their own [[air traffic control]] costs, which until then had been covered by the administration.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sivil Rygge-flyplass m<U+00F8>ter motstand |work=[[Aftenposten]] |last=Dahl |first=Flemming |date=17 December 2000 |page=7 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> In September 2001, the [[Norwegian Competition Authority]] supported the airport, stating that it would allow more competition on international flights from Norway, and could make it easier to establish domestic competition in the lieu of Scandinavian Airline's take-over of Braathens.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tungt for Rygge |work=[[Aftenposten]] |last=Dahl |first=Flemming |date=12 September 2001 |page=44 |language=Norwegian}}</ref>

[[File:F16 take-off at Rygge Air Station.jpg|thumb|Two [[General Dynamics F-16 Fighting Falcon]]s taking off from Rygge]]
In June 2002, [[Norwegian Air Shuttle]] stated that they would start flights from Rygge, should the airport be built. At the same time, the military and the airport company were discussing where the optimal location for the terminal should be. Once decided, the Rygge Sivile Lufthavn hoped to send an application for a [[concession (contract)|concession]] to the [[Ministry of Transport and Communications (Norway)|Ministry of Transport and Communications]].<ref name=nasdist>{{cite news |title=Flere flyselskaper vil starte flyvninger fra Rygge |work=[[Aftenposten]] |last=Enghaug |first=P<U+00E5>l |date=22 June 2002 |page=2 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> In March 2003, [[Norwegian Labour Party|Rygge Labour Party]] stated they were opposed to the civilian airport, because of the local noise concerns.<ref>{{cite news |title=Neppe sivilfly p<U+00E5> Rygge |work=[[Verdens Gang]] |date=29 March 2003 |page=53 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> In May, the airport company confirmed that Ryanair, which was using Torp, had shown interest in using Rygge.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lavprisflyselskaper til Rygge |work=[[Aftenposten]] |date=15 May 2003 |page=32 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> In June, the Rygge Sivile Lufthavn stated that had changed their strategy, and that they now were going to primarily target [[low-cost airline]]s. The airport hoped to initially establish routes to Copenhagen, Stockholm, London and Amsterdam, and that international destinations would be prioritized before domestic destinations.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rygge lufthavn satser p<U+00E5> lavprisfly |work=[[Aftenposten]] |last=Enghaug |first=P<U+00E5>l |date=25 June 2003 |page=4 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> In February 2004, the [[Civil Aviation Authority of Norway|Civil Aviation Authority]] stated that 51 issues needed to be resolved before civilian traffic would be permitted.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sivil flytrafikk fra Rygge utsettes |work=[[Aftenposten]] |last=Enghaug |first=P<U+00E5>l |date=15 February 2004 |page=4 |language=Norwegian}}</ref>

In a report published by the ministry in March 2004, it was estimated that the airport would have 700,000 to 800,000 passengers per year, making it th eighth largest in the country, and could have 1.3 million passengers by 2030.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ser etter 800 000 p<U+00E5> Rygge  |work=[[Aftenposten]] |last=Enghaug |first=P<U+00E5>l |date=14 March 2004 |page=3 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> In a reply, the [[Federation of Norwegian Aviation Industries]] stated that they were opposed to establishing a new airport, and stated that there were sufficient airports in Eastern Norway. They stated that an airport outside Avinor (the new name for the Norwegian Civil Airport Administration) would result lower profits at Gardermoen, and thus higher fees for the rest of the airports. In addition, the airlines would have higher costs having to operate to additional airports in Eastern Norway.<ref>{{cite news |title=Norske flyselskaper skyr Rygge |work=[[Aftenposten]] |last=Enghaug |first=P<U+00E5>l |date=25 April 2004 |page=4 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> The proejct was also met with local protests. In particular, they were concerned about the emission to the lake [[Vansj<U+00F8>]], alternatively to a [[Ramsar site]] in [[Kurefjorden]], and the local noise pollution, with the airport being located close to Moss.<ref name=vansjo>{{cite news |title=Sivil luftfart truer milj<U+00F8>et |work=[[Dagsavisen]] |last=Sandb<U+00E6>k |first=<U+00D8>rnulf |last2=Abrahamsen |first2=Anders |date=28 August 2004 |page=52 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> [[Natur og Ungdom]] were also opposed to the airport, stating that it would increase the amount of air traffic and thus result in an increase in [[greenhouse gas]]es.<ref>{{cite news |title=Stans Rygge Lufthavn!  |work=[[Klassekampen]] |date=25 May 2006 |language=Norwegian}}</ref>

K<U+00F8>benhavns Lufthavne sold its ownership in the company during 2004, because they were not satisfied with the progress.<ref name=skjebne /> On 18 November 2004, the air force received the necessary concessions from the ministry to establish a civilian section. The concession contained a limit of 750,000 passengers per year, and had a duration of 10 years. It also requires the airport to be open from 07 to 23 every day and permit [[general aviation]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Klarsignal for Moss Lufthavn Rygge |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=18 November 2004 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> Negotiations between the air force and Rygge Sivile Lufthavn started in June 2005 to establish an agreement regarding operations and financing.<ref name=skjebne>{{cite news |title=Skjebne-time for Rygge |work=[[Aftenposten]] |last=Dahl |first=Flemming |date=9 May 2005 |page=3 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> In September, the air force and the company came to an agreement regarding the company's compensation to the military.<ref>{{cite news |title=Enighet om bruken av Rygge lufthavn |work=[[Aftenposten]] |last=Dahl |first=Flemming |date=15 September 2005 |page=13 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> The agreement was approved by the [[Ministry of Defence (Norway)|Ministry of Defence]] in January 2006.<ref>{{cite news |title=Klart for Moss lufthavn Rygge |work=[[Stavanger Aftenblad]] |date=7 January 2006 |page=8 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> On 22 February, all permissions had been granted, and the company was able to take an investment decision. The agreements involved, in addition to a new terminal, upgrades to the runway, taxiway and navigational systems, which would be paid for by Rygge Sivile Lufthavn.<ref>{{cite news |title=F<U+00F8>rste sivile fly fra Rygge sommeren 2007 |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=22 February 2006 |language=Norwegian}}</ref>

On 2 March, the [[Thon Group]] purchased 40% of the company. The remaining owners are the [[Orkla Group]] (40%), which owns Borregaard, <U+00D8>stfold County Municipality (11%) and [[<U+00D8>stfold Energi]] (9%).<ref>{{cite news |title=Thon inn som eier i Rygge lufthavn |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=2 March 2006 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> On 12 June, activists from Natur og Ungdom chained themselves to the control tower in protest against the establishment of civilian aviation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Aksjonerte i flyt<U+00E5>rnet p<U+00E5> Rygge i tre timer |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=12 June 2006 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> The contract to build the terminal was awarded [[Skanska]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Skanska bygger Rygge |work=[[Dagens N<U+00E6>ringsliv]] |last=Larsen |first=Trygve |date=27 June 2006 |page=3 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> In July, [[State Secretary (Norway)|State Secretary]] [[Steinulf Tungesvik]] stated that if necessary, the ministry would use its right to set the prices at Rygge so it would not capture revenue from Gardermoen.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lavpris p<U+00E5> Rygge kan krasjlande |work=[[Dagsavisen]] |last=St<U+00E5>lhane |first=Henrik |last2=Hanssen |first2=Hiim Sturla Sm<U+00E1>ri |date=17 July 2006 |page=6 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> At the same time, representatives from Torp, the Federation of Norwegian Aviation Industries and the [[Conservative Party of Norway|Conservative Party]] stated that the agreement between the military and the operating company was illegal subsidies.<ref>{{cite news |title=Full krig mellom Torp og Rygge  |work=[[Dagsavisen]] |last=St<U+00E5>lhane |first=Henrik |last2=Hanssen |first2=Hiim Sturla Sm<U+00E1>ri |date=19 July 2006 |page=10 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> In September, the Thon Group announced they would not build a planned {{convert|34|m|adj=on|sp=us}} tall hotel at the airport, as military regulations would not permit it.<ref>{{cite news |title=Dropper hotellplaner  |work=[[Dagens N<U+00E6>ringsliv]] |date=12 September 2006 |page=39 |language=Norwegian}}</ref>

In January 2007, the charter operators [[Star Tour]], Apollo and [[My Travel]] announced that they would start operating charter flights from 1 October. The initial construction was for seven gates, with possibilities to expand to fourteen.<ref name=gates /> The first phase cost NOK 700 million and included a {{convert|16000|m2|adj=on|sp=us}} terminal with a capacity for two million annual passengers, parking for 1650 cars and various travel facilities, such as [[duty free]] stores, bank and restaurants.<ref>{{cite news |title=Snart take off fra Rygge |work=[[Aftenposten]] |last=Finstad |first=<U+00D8>yvind |date=12 February 2007 |page=22 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> By April the airport still only had a single weekly charter route planned and the airport considered postponin Professor Frode Steen at the [[Norwegian School of Economics and Business Administration]] stated that the airlines were postponing to get a better negotiation position.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tar ikke av  |work=[[Aftenposten Aften]] |last=Larsen |first=P<U+00E5>l V. |last2=Hages<U+00E6>ther |first2=Fredrik |date=25 April 2007 |page=9 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> On 7 September, the final agreements between Rygge Sivile Lufthavn and the military were signed.<ref>{{cite news |title=Flyplassen p<U+00E5> Rygge endelig godkjent |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=7 September 2007 |language=Norwegian}}</ref>

The airport was opened on 5 October 2007.<ref>{{cite news |title=Moss lufthavn Rygge <U+00C5>pnes i morgen |work=[[Nationen]] |date=4 October 2007 |page=4 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> The first flight from the airport took place on 17 October to the [[Las Palmas de Gran Canaria]], Spain. The operator later increased with three more charter destinations early 2008. At the time of the first flight, the operator had sold 95% of the seats on their flights until the end of the year. 85% of the sales were to people living in <U+00D8>stfold.<ref name=charterstart>{{cite news |title=F<U+00F8>rste charterfly fra Rygge |work=[[Dagbladet]] |last=Buzzi |first=Kirsten |date=17 October 2007 |page=34 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> From that day, [[UniBuss]] started a [[coach (vehicle)|coach]] service from [[Oslo]] in correspondence with all departures and arrivals at the airport.<ref name=dbfaktaboks>{{cite news |title=Fakta Moss Lufthavn Rygge |work=[[Dagbladet]] |date=17 October 2007 |page=35 |language=Norwegian}}</ref>

The Civil Aviation Authority introduced a non-flight limitation on the airport from 23 to 07, of consideration to the airport's neighbors. This was despite the municipal councils in R<U+00E5>de and Rygge supporting night flights.<ref>{{cite news |title=Vil ha nattflyging p<U+00E5> Rygge |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=12 October 2007 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> The decision was appealed, with the airport wanting to operate from 06:30 to 23:30, stating that they could lose half of Norwegian's departures.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nytt nei til Rygge  |work=[[Nationen]] |date=28 November 2007 |page=12 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> The ministry granted such a permit on 25 January 2008.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rygge flyplass f<U+00E5>r utvidede <U+00E5>pningstider  |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=25 January 2008 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> This prompted a lawsuit from 150 households within the noise zone, who stated that people with similar noise pollution around Gardermoen had been granted NOK 225,000 in compensation each.<ref>{{cite news |title=Vil vurdere rettssak mot Moss Lufthavn Rygge |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=27 January 2008 |language=Norwegian}}</ref>

Norwegian Air Shuttle established a base at Rygge on 14 February 2008, with a second aircraft being stationed at the airport from 13 March. From February to April, Norwegian Air Shuttle started international flights to [[Alicante]], [[Athens]], [[Barcelona]], [[Belgrade]], [[Budapest]], [[Istanbul]], [[London]], [[M<U+00E1>laga]], [[Marrakech]], [[Palanga]], [[Szczecin]], [[Valencia]], [[Warsaw]], with tbetween two and four weekly services to each destination. In addition, the airline started two daily services to Bergen.<ref name=norwegianhub>{{cite web |url=http://www.norwegian.no/om-norwegian/presse/pressemeldinger/nyhetsarkiv-2007/Norwegian-satser-stort-pa-Rygge/ |title=Norwgian satser stort p<U+00E5> Rygge |publisher=[[Norwegian Air Shuttle]] |year=2007 |accessdate=24 November 2010 |archivedate=24 November 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5uTeI9NDo}}</ref> Norwegian's services to Belgrade, Istanbul, Marrakech, Szczecin and Valencia were all terminated at Gardermoen the same time as they opened at Rygge.<ref>{{cite news |title=Norwegian kutter ruter fra Gardermoen  |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=30 October 2007 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> The airport stated that they had also been approached by Ryanair, who wanted to move the bulk of their services from Torp, but the airport stated that there was only room for one airline, and that they had prioritized Norwegian.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rygge vil ikke ha Ryan Air |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=17 October 2007 |language=Norwegian}}</ref>

[[File:Norwegian 737-300 at Rygge.jpg|thumb|left|[[Norwegian Air Shuttle]] [[Boeing 737-300]]]]
The first Norwegian Air Shuttle plane took off at the 14 February 2008 heading for Budapest. The same day, the [[Norwegian State Railways]] started offering a shuttle bus service from Rygge Station on the <U+00D8>stfold Line to the airport.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rygge <U+00E5>pner <U+00D8>stfold |work=[[Bergens Tidende]] |date=9 February 2008 |page=18 |language=Norwegian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ungarsk <U+00E5>pning av Rygge |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=14 February 2008 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> At the same time, Norwegian Business Aviation started offering [[executive jet]]s from Rygge.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lokker bedrifter med privatjet |work=[[Dagens N<U+00E6>ringsliv]] |last=Jebsen |first=Anniken H. |date=23 January 2008 |page=36 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> From March, Wider<U+00F8>e started two daily services from Rygge to Copenhagen, the [[airline hub|hub]] for their owner, Scandinavian Airlines.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wider<U+00F8>e til K<U+00F8>benhavn fra Rygge og Haugesund |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=25 January 2008 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> Apollo started flights to [[Chania]] from 11 May.<ref name=charterstart /> Star Tour started weekly charter flights to [[Antalya]], [[Chania]] and [[Palma de Mallorca]] during the first half of 2008.<ref>{{cite news |title=Charter-utvider |work=[[Verdens Gang]] |date=26 September 2007 |page=16 |language=Norwegian}}</ref>

From 1 September, Wider<U+00F8>e terminated its Copenhagen route, while Norwegian terminated its London service.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rygger ut   |work=[[Aftenposten]] |last=Hages<U+00E6>ther |first=P<U+00E5>l V. |date=26 June 2008 |page=10 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> In October, Norwegian Air Shuttle introduced new international services to Las Palmas de Gran Canaria,<ref>{{cite news |title=Charter-utvider |work=[[Dagbladet]] |date=11 June 2008 |page=41 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> [[Berlin]], [[Krak<U+00F3>w]] and [[Praha]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Nye ruter fra Rygge |work=[[Dagbladet]] |date=20 August 2008 |page=36 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> New domestic routes were introduced to Trondheim, Stavanger, [[Troms<U+00F8>]] and [[Bod<U+00F8>]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Norwegian utvider rutenettet |work=[[Bladet Troms<U+00F8>]] |date=10 September 2008 |page=6 |language=Norwegian}}</ref>

The airport stated that at the growth rate they were experiencing, they would reach their passenger ceiling in 2009, and would not have room for any other airlines than Norwegian.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rygge blir <U+00AB>Bj<U+00F8>rn Kjos Airport<U+00BB>  |work=[[Aftenposten]] |last=Mikaelsen |first=Knut-Erik |date=11 September 2008 |page=6 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> In November, the airport stated that they in 2008 would lose NOK 100 million, and that they needed between NOK 200 and 300 million in new share capital. However, neither Orkla nor Thon were willing to invest more in the airport unless they passenger ceiling was lifted.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rygge i akutt pengen<U+00F8>d |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=19 November 2008 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> In a vote in the [[Parliament of Norway]] on 11 December, the ceiling was not lifted, with the proposal only receiving the votes of the opposition.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ikke flere passasjerer fra Rygge |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=11 December 2008 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> However, the ministry stated that they were going to consider the limitations in the concession. In January, the owners invested 50 million in the company. The airport had 450,000 passengers in 2008.<ref>{{cite news |title=Skyter inn 50 millioner |work=[[Dagens N<U+00E6>ringsliv]] |last=Finstad |first=<U+00D8>yvind |date=6 January 2009 |page=22 |language=Norwegian}}</ref>

In January, Rygge was, with 24,400 passengers, larger than Torp in domestic traffic.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rygge forbi Torp p<U+00E5> innenriks |work=[[Verdens Gang]] |last=Finstad |first=<U+00D8>yvind |date=18 February 2009 |page=12 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> In February, the Civil Aviation Authority recommended that the airport's ceiling be lifted,<ref>{{cite news |title=Vil la Rygge f<U+00E5> slippe passasjertaket  |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=24 February 2009 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> and this was made effective by the ministry on 1 July. Instead, the airport was limited to 15,000 air movements per year. The ministry stated that the rationale was that the calculations for the original concession were based on smaller aircraft, and that the passenger ceiling was based on an estimated 20,000 take-offs and landings.<ref>{{cite news |title=<U+00C5>pner for mer trafikk p<U+00E5> Rygge |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=1 July 2009 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> From January through April, the domestic services from Rygge had captured 6% of the market share from Eastern Norway.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rygge tar passasjerer fra Gardermoen |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=7 October 2009 |language=Norwegian}}</ref>

[[File:Incheckning Moss Airport, Rygge.JPG|thumb|Check-in]]
In October and November, Ryanair established itself at the airport, and started flights to Alicante, Barcelona, [[Brussels]], [[Bremen]], [[Madrid]], [[Milano]] and [[London]].<ref name=ryanairhub>{{cite news |title=Rygge-London for <U+00E9>n krone |work=[[Akershus Amtstidende]] |date=17 July 2009 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> Norwegian stated that they were not worried about competition from Ryanair, and announced that they would continue with flights to the Mediterranean, Eastern Europe and domestically. However, they would not start the announced services to Amsterdam and London, and instead concentrate their growth at Gardermoen. The company stated that they made 3% of their revenue of Rygge.<ref>{{cite news |title=Norwegian trapper ned p<U+00E5> Rygge |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=17 July 2009 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> On 9 September, the ministry increased the air movement ceiling to 21,000 movements per year.<ref>{{cite news |title=Navarsete gir gavepakke til Rygge |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=9 September 2009 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> On 24 November, Ryanair announced that they would establish a base at Rygge in March 2010.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ryanair etablerer base p<U+00E5> Moss Lufthavn |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]] |date=9 September 2009 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> The airline would start services to [[<U+00C5>rhus]], [[Berlin]], [[Dublin]], [[D<U+00FC>sseldorf]], [[Eindhoven]], [[Gdansk]], Krak<U+00F3>w, [[La Rochelle]], M<U+00E1>laga, [[Munich]], Palma de Mallorca, [[Paris]], [[Riga]], [[Wroclaw]], Valencia and [[Venice]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Tar av p<U+00E5> Rygge |work=[[Aftenposten]] |last=Mikaelsen |first=Knut-Erik |date=25 November 2009 |page=11 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> In December, the company announced further routes to [[Faro]] and [[Zadar]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Nye Ryanair-ruter |work=[[Agderposten]] |date=17 December 2009 |page=10 |language=Norwegian}}</ref>

In 2009, the airport company lost NOK 102 million.<ref>{{cite news |title=Taper dobbelt s<U+00E5> mye som det omsetter |work=[[Dagens N<U+00E6>ringsliv]]  |date=27 July 2010 |page=14 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> From 5 May, Ryanair started flights to [[Kaunas]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ryanair starter ny rute |work=[[Aftenposten]] |date=10 February 2010 |page=16 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> In mid-2010, Norwegian terminated its services to Berlin, Budapest, Palanga, Praha and Valencia, and reduced the frequency to Alicante and M<U+00E1>laga. However, it started new routes to [[Dalaman]] and [[Thessaloniki]].<ref>{{cite news |title=- Gir opp p<U+00E5> grunn av Ryanair |work=[[Aftenposten]] |last=Mikaelsen |first=Knut-Erik |date=17 February 2010 |page=4 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> In July, Norwegian stated that they were considering terminating all services from Rygge. In particular, the company stated that they were not satisfied with having higher fees than Ryanair, and that they were in negotiations with Torp to move their operations there.<ref>{{cite news |title=Norwegian truer med <U+00E5> fly til Torp |work=[[Dagens N<U+00E6>ringsliv]] |last=Finstad |first=<U+00D8>yvind |date=27 July 2010 |page=14 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> In September, Norwegian announced that it was terminating the services to Bod<U+00F8> and Troms<U+00F8>.<ref>{{cite news |title=Legger ned Rygge-rute  |work=[[Nordlys]] |date=29 September 2010 |page=4 |language=Norwegian}}</ref>

In November 2010, the instrument landing system (ILS) was upgraded from Category I to Category II. This included the installation of 800 [[light emitting diode]]s (LED) on the runway and taxiway, making Rygge the first airport in Europe with such an installation. It decreased the requirement for visibility from {{convert|800|to|300|m|sp=us}}. The upgrades cost NOK 65 million, and made Rygge the second airport with ILS Cat II in Norway, after [[Stavanger Airport, Sola]] (Gardermoen has Cat III).<ref name=led /> The same month, Ryanair started new routes to London, [[Liverpool]], [[Rome]], [[Tampere]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ryanair starter  |work=[[Dagbladet]] |date=8 November 2010 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> At the same time, Norwegian terminated its service to Stavanger.<ref>{{cite news |title=KLM utvider til Amsterdam  |work=[[Stavanger Aftenblad]] |last=Helgesen |first=Jan-Petter |date=6 November 2010 |page=14 |language=Norwegian}}</ref>

